HOUSE BILL 24-
1 The Legislature finds that pursuant to 9 CMC §§8203 and 8204,
2 respectively, motorists are not allowed to operate a vehicle unless the vehicle is
3 covered by and possesses minimum liability motor vehicle insurance. The
4 Legislature further finds that pursuant to 9 CMC §8209, all motorists who violate
5 9 CMC §8203 and 8204 are granted a seven-day grace period to submit satisfactory
6 evidence of minimum motor vehicle liability insurance to the Department of Public
7 Safety, providing coverage to avoid imposing such citation for violating 9 CMC
8 §8203. The Legislature finds that this type of practice is extremely detrimental to
9 the CNMI as uninsured motorists will be allowed to operate their vehicle for an
10 extra period of time. Within such time frame, these uninsured motorists may be
11 involved in a motor vehicle accident which may result in highly severe and
12 unfortunate consequences regardless of who bears the fault. To avoid such tragic
13 outcomes, it is imperative to remove the seven-day grace period provided under 9
14 CMC §8209 to deter uninsured motorists from operating their vehicles without the
15 required motor vehicle liability insurance. This removal will promote and enhance
16 better safety and financial management for all owners and operators of a motor
17 vehicle.
18 Therefore, the purpose of this Act is to amend 9 CMC §8209 by removing
19 the seven-day grace period for motorists who violate 9 CMC §§8203 and 8204 and
20 for other purposes and require that the civil citations be effective immediately.
